    "Looking at the mapped transformation, I need to identify the reaction center - the local bond/atom changes.\n\nThe key mapped atoms are:\n- [CH2-:10][S:20](=O)(=O)[Cl:21] → [CH2:10]=[S:20](=O)=O + [Cl-:21]\n\nSo the transformation is:\n- CH2⁻-S(=O)(=O)-Cl → CH2=S(=O)=O + Cl⁻\n\nThe reaction center involves:\n1. Bond change between C:10 and S:20: from C⁻-S single bond to C=S double bond\n2. Bond change between S:20 and Cl:21: from S-Cl bond broken (Cl leaves as Cl⁻)\n3. Charge change on C:10: from [CH2-] to neutral [CH2]\n4. Charge change on Cl:21: from neutral Cl to [Cl-]\n\nThis is essentially an elimination where the carbanion attacks sulfur, forming a C=S double bond while chloride departs. This is a sulfonyl chloride reacting with a carbanion to form a sulfene (CH2=S(=O)=O) and chloride ion.\n\nThe reaction center: C:10–S:20 bond changes from single to double; S:20–Cl:21 bond breaks; C:10 loses negative charge; Cl:21 gains negative charge."
